ce:section.ce:para:
The sensitivity of the “turn-on” nanoprobe for Zn2+ detection was investigated. The PL intensities of the ClNCQDs/morin system were gradually enhanced when various concentration of Zn2+ (0–5.55 mM) were added into the ClNCQDs/morin system, which is shown in Fig. 5
                        A. The emission peak is blue-shifted from 551 nm to 490 nm, which agrees with the shooting figures shot under 365 nm UV light and are inserted in Fig. 5A. In Fig. 5B, a good linear relationship between (P-P0)/P0 and Zn2+ concentration is obtained with a linear equation of (P-P0)/P0 = 0.0107 × c(Zn
                        2+
                        ) + 0.0488 (R2
                         = 0.9937) in the range of 0.44–154.07 μM, where P and P0 are the PL intensities of the ClNCQDs/morin system with and without Zn2+, respectively. P or P0 is the highest value of each spectrum. The LOD and LOQ are 0.17 μM and 0.56 μM, respectively. The color of the ClNCQDs/morin system varied from faint-yellow to dark-yellow after adding different concentration of Zn2+, which is inserted in Fig. 5C. When different concentrations of Zn2+ (0.5–55.8 μM) were entered into the ClNCQDs/morin system, an absorption peak at 356 nm (A365) gradually decreased and a new absorption peak at 385 nm (A385) was appeared and gradually increased, which is shown in Fig. 5C. An isoelectric point can be found in Fig. 5C. As depicted in Fig. 5D and 5E, a good linear relationship between the A385/A356 and the concentration of Zn2+ can be found in the range of 0.50–11.40 μM and 16.40–55.80 μM with the linear equation, LOD, and LOQ of A385/A356 = 0.0209 × c(Zn
                        2+
                        ) + 0.6893 (R2
                         = 0.9973), 0.24 µM, and 0.81 µM and A385/A356 = 0.0078 × c(Zn
                        2+
                        ) + 0.8778 (R2
                         = 0.9933), 0.65 µM, and 2.17 µM, respectively. Different linear ranges of the fluorometric and colorimetric readout modes can be found, whereas the coverage (0.50–11.4 µM and 16.4–55.8 µM) between the two modes is good, which is beneficial to the mutual verification of the Zn2+ detection results by the two constructed methods. Therefore, the ClNCQDs/morin system can be used as a “turn-on” nanoprobe for fluorometric and colorimetric dual-readout detection of Zn2+ with remarkable superiorities of simplicity, rapidity, and sensitivity, which has the potential in detecting of Zn2+ in some actual samples (vide infra). By comparing the reported CQDs-based fluorescent probe and the proposed nanoprobe for the detection of Zn2+ (Table 2
                        ), we find that the constructed nanoprobe has comparability with other reported methods.
